item.title: Cops make arrests over Tik Tok brawl
item.description: Two men have been charged after the riot squad was called in to break up a wild brawl in western Sydney.

item.title: Schools, shops now on Qld COVID list
item.description: A south Brisbane school will remain open today despite a positive COVID-19 case having visited the after school hours care.

item.title: Giant snakes crash through roof
item.description: Massive carpet snakes, so heavy they smashed a hole in a kitchen ceiling at a home near Brisbane, have given a retiree a terrifying surprise.

item.title: Grand Final move ‘all but certain’
item.description: The AFL Commission is set to make a decision on which city will host this year’s Grand Final, with many expecting Queensland to reap the rewards of their $200m role in saving the season.

item.title: The measures propping up bad businesses
item.description: A report issued by one of Australia’s leading credit agencies is warning COVID-19 insolvency relief measures will cause a domino effect of business shutdowns.

item.title: Horror hotel cleaning bungle revealed
item.description: A senior public servant lost confidence that the Victorian Department of Health and Human Services knew what they “really need or want” in the early days of the hotel quarantine program, according to an email revealed at the inquiry into the troubled scheme.

item.title: Eddie Obeid trial to drag into 2021
item.description: The long-running conspiracy trial of Eddie Obeid looks set to drag into next year with the case against the ex-Labor heavyweight not scheduled to wrap up until January.

item.title: Fabric softener clue in murder case
item.description: A woman who lay down next to accused murderer Caroline Dela Rose Nilsson and calmed her after she was discovered with her hands and feet bound has told a Supreme Court jury she could smell fabric softener.

item.title: Why full bushfire devastation unknown
item.description: The full devastation wrought by Australia’s unprecedented summer bushfires is unclear because of inconsistencies in how data is collected and shared, a new report says.

item.title: ’Babyfaced Libs’: Super row fires up
item.description: Federal MPs hustling to scrap the legislated rise in superannuation benefits are raking in far more than the amount paid to everyday Australians.
